of long bones","At birth, 100% of bone marrow is red marrow","Yellow marrow contains more haematopoietic stem cells than red marrow"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAt birth, 100% of bone marrow is red marrow\u003C/strong\u003E is correct. Newborns have entirely red marrow, which is responsible for haematopoiesis. As individuals age, some of this red marrow is replaced by yellow marrow, which primarily stores fat and has fewer haematopoietic stem cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIn adults, yellow marrow comprises about 10% of bone marrow\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as in adults, approximately 50% of bone marrow is yellow marrow, not 10%. \u003Cstrong\u003ETotal bone marrow mass in adults is approximately 5 kg\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect since the total bone marrow mass in adults is about 3 kg, which constitutes roughly 4-5% of total body weight. \u003Cstrong\u003ERed marrow in adults is primarily located in the diaphyses of long bones\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because in adults, red marrow is mainly found in the axial skeleton and the proximal ends of long bones, not in the diaphyses. \u003Cstrong\u003EYellow marrow contains more haematopoietic stem cells than red marrow\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as red marrow contains more haematopoietic stem cells, which are essential for blood cell production.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Red marrow comprises all bone marrow at birth but converts to yellow marrow with age, leaving only 50% as red marrow in adults.","Total bone marrow mass in adults is approximately 3 kg, or 4-5% of total body weight.","Red marrow in adults is primarily located in the axial skeleton and proximal ends of long bones."],"references":["Frisch, B., \u0026 Bartl, R. (2012). Atlas of bone marrow pathology (Vol. 15). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media.","Porwit, A., McCullough, J., \u0026 Erber, W. N. (2011). Blood and bone 